node.text:
The blue room, Provence.

A bouquet in an 19thc potiche with flowers from the garden, bougainvillea, solanum and Papyrus.
The papyrus have growned in the garden a hundred years ago in a stone basin called »Ramieu » used to soak the wicker before being weaved.

On the wall, a provencal 18thc hand painted family tree and an early 18thc Aubusson tapestry.
A Directoire daybed and 18thc armchair and child chair.

2nd and 3rd images,
The countryside around the village.

4th and 5rd images,
Work and progress in the Vime house, Élise preparing the lime plaster with pigments.

6th image,
Alma in the blue room.

7th image,
In the vegetable garden.

#ateliervime

node.text:
The place and the plant.

Merci to @m_magazine for this beautiful story on our wicker growing project at the farm, why and how we have built it.

Merci @m_arieaparis for your understanding of our motivations and goals, for your dedication to fully relate the connexion between the plant, the people and the territory.

The story continues with the three of us with @unbrinsauvage , we will soon plant some other varieties and welcome the bees with wicker hives we are currently weaving, based on ones made in our workshop in the late 19thC.

node.text:
A déjeuner in the wicker field at the farm.
Opening the doors for @tmagazine.

Thank you to our friends for sharing this moment;
@emmanuelpierre_illustrateur
@roland_beaufre 
@unbrinsauvage 
@stvnpnnr 
@virginie_fouin_fz 
@nozantika 

Special merci to Roland for the beautiful images and Emmanuel for the wonderful Menu and cavalier’s. 🖤

Story beautifully written by @aimee_farrell.

1st image,
In the wicker field and the orchard, the new Marie-Victoire de Bascher/Atelier Vime Corals tablecloth paired with Anthéor armchairs by Mathieu Mategot, 1930 rattan and wood chairs and a Medici vase by Atelier Vime Editions.

2nd image,
In the kitchen, preparing the déjeuner, fresh seafood and kombucha by @danielwrightkombucha made with plants from the area.

3rd image,
The special Ile de Sein soup originally made by the sailor’s wife’s at the beginning of the century.

4th image,
All the salad ingredients cultivated by @virginie_fouin_fz in her lovely seaside garden.

5th image,
Emmanuel in the studio making his collages for the menu.

7th image,
Gaël, @unbrinsauvage and Cecilia.

9th,
A vue of the studio with our collection of mini baskets from all periods and regions and a bouquet made with our last wheat harvest with Gaël.

#ateliervimeatlantique

node.text:
Bonjour Provence.

In the grey room,
An antic Uzbek Suzani,
a drawing by Setsuko Klossowska de Rola, a 1926 painting by Charles Kvapil and 18thc furnitures.

The painting on the top of the door and the cupboard built in the wall dates back to the building of the house, 1730.
This room was originally used as a dining room and the cupboard as a china cabinet.

2nd image,
A vue of the yellow room.

4th image,
In the blue room, a Directoire daybed, an 18thc child chair and an Empire console.

5th image,
Work in progress in the new Vime house, a traditional terracotta and stone floor motifs from the area being restored.

6th image,
Cicada and sunset light in the grey room.

#ateliervime#provence

node.text:
The little bedroom, at the farm.

Antic rope and wood farm chair and table, 19thc little ceramics from Quimper, the Medici vase by Atelier Vime Editions, a wooden painted wall light by Suzanne Bonnichon and a 1960 rattan and brass bed.

3rd image,
Wild flowers from around the house.

5th image,
The 18thc laborer house.

6th image,
Sunset on the sea arm down the farm.

#ateliervimeatlantique

node.text:
Brittany, a bedroom by the seaside.

On an antic kilim, a farm table with a chair by Breton decorator Jean Lachaud, designed for a nearby hotel in the 40’s.
We made the decor above the door with pine cones from the garden.
The curtains are made out antic linen sheets and we painted them with stencils @waynepate created for us, wicker pelmet by Atelier Vime Editions.

4th image,
Under the linden, the 18thc farm labourer’s house.

5th image,
Part of the first floor with it’s original wooden floor and ceilings.
An Empire armchair covered with an antic Uzbek Suzani, a 1929 collage by Albert Huyot.
The shelfs were made by my father using planks and terracotta bricks.
In the back, a 19thc ceramic stove.

7th image,
New bee hives installed in the garden.

The bedroom by @joannamaclennanphotography for @theworldofinteriors 

#ateliervimeatlantique

node.text:
Sunday under the arches, Provence.

With it’s original 18thc stone floors and 19thc blue patina.

Provencal terracotta pots and metal chairs, Medici pedestal and vase and rattan Croisillon armchair by Atelier Vime.

2nd image,
Cicada’s in the courtyard, summer is setting in.

3rd image,
A vue of the main staircase.

4th image,
Alma in the yellow drawing room.

5th and 6th images,
Sunset on the west facade.

#ateliervime#provence

node.text:
Authentique Provence,
Preserved since 1730.

The main staircase with it’s wrought iron stair railing.
Same motif as the large balcony one.
Original wall colors made with pigments from the area.
An 18thc armchair by cabinetmaker Martin Julien, early 19thc Iranian « Bothé » carpet and a pair of 18thc Louis XV Encoignures.

3rd image,
The fire place in the yellow room,
a provencal glazed ceramic fountain, roses from the garden and 19thc little birds made in Vallauris.

4th image,
The Albizia starting to bloom.

6th image,
The original Louis XV plaster molding ceiling at 8 meters high, restored three years ago.

7th image,
Sunset in the yellow room.

#ateliervime

node.text:
Summer vibes in Provence.

In the green room,
A wood and straw bed by Charlotte Perriand, 18thc guilded wood mirror, chest of drawers, metal and porcelain chandelier and the tropique chair by Mathieu Matégot.
Wild flowers from around the house on a 1930 rattan and wood log side table from our workshop archives.

3rd and 4th images,
The baby birds are fine, they will probably leave the nest in these few days.

5th image,
The bougainvillea in the garden.

6th image,
A vue of the courtyard with the beautiful Albizia or silk tree.
He will be in bloom in around two weeks.
On the table, provencal 19thc glazed ceramics.

#ateliervime#provence

node.text:
Sunday in the courtyard, Provence.

Under the wild fig tree, an armchair by Arne Jacobsen designed in 1936.
On the large balcony, a typical 18thc Louis XV wrought iron railing.

2nd image,
In the green room, the Medium Medici vase by Atelier Vime Editions, a drawing by Édouard Manet and a 18thc chair with it’s original tapestry.
The table cover is a beautiful 18thc block print fabric from @les.olivades family archives.

3rd and 4th images,
Work in progress in the new Vime house, discovering the original painted color on the fireplace.
A vue of the room with the canes from the river banks that we found in the house among other beautiful baskets and utilitary objects.
The previous owners were basket makers, the spouses were usually making sun shades with the canes growing around the house.
The story continues.

5th and 6th images,
A « rougequeue noir» family birds settled during the renovation.

7th image,
Sunset in the yellow room.

#ateliervime#provence

node.text:
The blue room, Provence.

An early 18thc Aubusson tapestry and a hand painted provencal family tree, 1768.
Paired with an 18thc armchair by cabinetmaker Martin Julien, an 18thc child chair, a 1926 painting by Charles Kvapil and a 17thc Iranian vase with broom flowers from around the house.

3rd image, 
A room at the first floor.

4th image,
Back home along the river and the broom flowers.

6th image,
Sunset in the attic of the new Vime house.

7th image,
End of the day in the yellow room.

node.text:
A kitchen by the seaside, 
Atelier Vime Atlantique, @theworldofinteriors 

The 4 seasons in the wicker field. 

It’s been 2 years since we’ve decided to grow our own wicker in our breton farm by the sea. 
Together with our friend Gael Davoli @unbrinsauvage, we have plowed, planted and grown two parcels of « petite grisette », a variety of wicker suitable for sharp and delicate pieces, such as our little shades or baskets.
Today, we are happy and proud to share some images of the life in the wicker field. 

From planting in March till the January harvest.

1st image,
The kitchen with baskets and birdcages from our workshop archives.
An 18thc sideboard, the Solo pendant light by Atelier Vime Editions, 1922/1924 plates by Breton artist Suzanne Creston and a 1950 footed bowl by Breton artist Paul Yvain from Atelier Vime and @nozantika collection.

#ateliervimeatlantique
